          From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia                            Jump to:     navigation,      search              Rong Zongjing   Rong Zongjing (Chinese: 榮宗敬; September 23, 1873 - 1938) was a Chinese industrialist from Wuxi, Jiangsu. He was the older brother of Rong Desheng and the uncle of Rong Yiren. Rong went to Shanghai at the age of fourteen and worked as an apprentice at a native bank. Rong started his own native bank in 1896 with his father and brother, and then established a flour milling and textile empire in China that employed tens of thousands of workers. Further reading[edit]  Bergere, Marie Claire. (author) (1989). The Golden Age of the Chinese Bourgoisie 1911-1937l. Cambridge.  Cochran, Sherman (author) (2000). Encountering Chinese Networks: Western, Japanese and Chinese Corporations in China 1880-1937. Berkeley.  Bush, Richard C. (author) (1987). Politics of Cotton Textiles in Kuomintang China 1927 -1937. New York.  Chan, Wellington K.K. (author) (1977). Merchants, Mandarins and Modern Enterprise in Late Ch’ing China. Cambridge MA.      This Chinese biographical article is a stub. You can help Wikipedia by expanding it.   v t e                         Retrieved from "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Rong_Zongjing&oldid=723549564"          Categories: 1873 births1938 deathsBusinesspeople from JiangsuPeople from WuxiChinese people stubsHidden categories: Articles containing traditional Chinese-language textAll stub articles            
